<content>
<para id="fs-id1166168191788">Why are certain materials magnetic and others not? And why do certain substances become magnetized by a field, whereas others are unaffected? To answer such questions, we need an understanding of magnetism on a microscopic level.</para>
<para id="fs-id1166168105871">Within an atom, every electron travels in an orbit and spins on an internal axis. Both types of motion produce current loops and therefore magnetic dipoles. For a particular atom, the net magnetic dipole moment is the vector sum of the magnetic dipole moments. Values of <m:math><m:mi>μ</m:mi></m:math> for several types of atoms are given in <link target-id="fs-id1166168184037"/>. Notice that some atoms have a zero net dipole moment and that the magnitudes of the nonvanishing moments are typically <m:math><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>−23</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>A</m:mtext><m:mo>·</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>m</m:mtext><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></para>
