<exercise id="fs-id1166168344016">
<problem id="fs-id1166168344018">
<para id="fs-id1166168344020">A long, straight, cylindrical conductor contains a cylindrical cavity whose axis is displaced by <emphasis effect="italics">a</emphasis> from the axis of the conductor, as shown in the accompanying figure. The current density in the conductor is given by <m:math><m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>J</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">→</m:mo></m:mover></m:mstyle><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>J</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>k</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover></m:mstyle><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> where <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>J</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> is a constant and <m:math><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>k</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover></m:mstyle></m:math> is along the axis of the conductor. Calculate the magnetic field at an arbitrary point P in the cavity by superimposing the field of a solid cylindrical conductor with radius <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>R</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> and current density <m:math><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>J</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">→</m:mo></m:mover></m:mstyle></m:math> onto the field of a solid cylindrical conductor with radius <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>R</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> and current density <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>−</m:mtext><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>J</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">→</m:mo></m:mover></m:mstyle><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> Then use the fact that the appropriate azimuthal unit vectors can be expressed as <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>k</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:msub><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>k</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:msub><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> to show that everywhere inside the cavity the magnetic field is given by the constant <m:math><m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>B</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">→</m:mo></m:mover></m:mstyle><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>J</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>k</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>a</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> where <m:math><m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>a</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>r</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:msub><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>r</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>r</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:msub><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> is the position of <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis> relative to the center of the conductor and <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mi>r</m:mi></m:mstyle><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:msub><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>^</m:mo></m:mover><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> is the position of <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis> relative to the center of the cavity.</para>
