</exercise>
<exercise xmlns:data="http://www.w3.org/TR/html5/dom.html#custom-data-attribute" id="fs-id1166164826688"><problem id="fs-id1166164826690">
<para id="fs-id1166164826693">Magnetic field inside a torus. Consider a torus of rectangular cross-section with inner radius <emphasis effect="italics">a</emphasis> and outer radius <emphasis effect="italics">b</emphasis>. <emphasis effect="italics">N</emphasis> turns of an insulated thin wire are wound evenly on the torus tightly all around the torus and connected to a battery producing a steady current <emphasis effect="italics">I</emphasis> in the wire. Assume that the current on the top and bottom surfaces in the figure is radial, and the current on the inner and outer radii surfaces is vertical. Find the magnetic field inside the torus as a function of radial distance <emphasis effect="italics">r</emphasis> from the axis.</para> <media id="fs-id1262164776985" alt="">
